  "summary": "Drafts comprehensive corporate resolutions authorizing the opening, maintenance, and transaction activities for corporate bank accounts. Ensures compliance with corporate bylaws, state law, and bank due diligence requirements through precise language on authority, officers, and adoption procedures. Use this skill when preparing formal board actions to satisfy financial institutions' demands for account management authorization.",
  "content": "# Corporate Resolutions for Bank Account - Enhanced Prompt\n\nYou are tasked with drafting a comprehensive Corporate Resolution for Bank Account that serves as a formal corporate governance document authorizing specific banking activities and designating individuals with authority to act on behalf of the corporation. This document must satisfy both corporate formalities and banking institution requirements while providing clear, legally sufficient authorization for financial transactions.\n\n## Understanding the Legal and Practical Context\n\nCorporate resolutions for banking purposes represent official board action that financial institutions require before allowing individuals to open accounts, execute transactions, or otherwise act on behalf of a corporation. These documents serve a dual purpose: they demonstrate compliance with the corporation's internal governance structure and provide banks with the legal assurance they need to accept instructions from designated corporate representatives. Banks typically require original or certified copies of these resolutions and will reject documents that lack specificity, contain ambiguous authorization language, or fail to demonstrate proper corporate authority. The resolution must align with the corporation's articles of incorporation and bylaws, comply with applicable state corporate law, and include sufficient detail to satisfy the due diligence requirements of modern financial institutions.\n\nBefore drafting, you should search any uploaded corporate documents to identify the corporation's exact legal name, state of incorporation, current officers and directors, existing bylaws provisions regarding banking authority, and any prior resolutions that may need to be superseded. Understanding the corporation's governance structure and any special authorization requirements in its governing documents is essential to creating a legally effective resolution.\n\n## Establishing Corporate Authority and Document Foundation\n\nBegin the resolution with a formal header that establishes the document's authority within the corporate governance framework. The header must include the corporation's complete legal name exactly as it appears in the articles of incorporation, the state of incorporation, and the specific date of adoption. Clearly identify whether this resolution is being adopted at a formal board meeting or by written consent of the directors, as this distinction affects the procedural requirements and certification language.\n\nThe preamble should establish the legal foundation by referencing the specific provisions of the corporation's bylaws or articles of incorporation that authorize the board to adopt banking resolutions. If the resolution is adopted at a meeting, document that proper notice was given, specify whether the meeting was regular or special, and confirm that a quorum was present throughout the proceedings. For written consents, confirm that the requisite percentage of directors have consented to the action, noting that many states require unanimous written consent unless the bylaws provide otherwise. Include recitals that explain the business necessity for the banking relationship, such as the corporation's need for banking services to conduct ordinary business operations, manage corporate funds, receive customer payments, or pay vendors and employees.\n\n## Crafting Comprehensive Banking Authorizations\n\nThe operative provisions of the resolution must provide detailed and specific authorization for all banking activities the corporation wishes to permit while maintaining appropriate corporate controls. This section forms the core of the document and must be drafted with precision to avoid both over-restriction that hampers business operations and over-authorization that creates fiduciary risks.\n\nAddress account establishment and management by explicitly authorizing designated officers to open, maintain, modify, and close specific types of accounts at named financial institutions or a defined class of institutions. Specify whether the authorization extends to checking accounts, savings accounts, money market accounts, certificates of deposit, or other account types. Consider whether the corporation needs flexibility to establish accounts at multiple institutions or whether banking relationships should be concentrated at specific banks.\n\nDesignate authorized signatories with clarity regarding both identity and scope of authority. You may designate individuals by specific name, by corporate title, or by a combination of both approaches. Specify whether any single authorized signatory may act alone or whether joint signatures are required for certain transactions or amounts. For example, you might authorize any one signature for transactions under a specified dollar threshold while requiring two signatures for larger amounts. Address check signing authority, wire transfer authorization, ACH transaction approval, online banking access, and authority to execute banking documents and agreements.\n\nEstablish clear transaction parameters that define the scope of authorized banking activities. Beyond basic deposit and withdrawal authority, address whether designated individuals may apply for loans, execute promissory notes, pledge corporate assets as collateral, establish lines of credit, or enter into other borrowing arrangements on behalf of the corporation. If borrowing authority is granted, specify any dollar limitations, approval requirements, or restrictions on the types of obligations that may be incurred. Consider whether certain transactions require board approval beyond the general authorization provided in this resolution.\n\nInclude broad authorization for designated officers to execute all documents, agreements, certificates, and instruments that the financial institution may require to establish and maintain the banking relationship. Banks often have their own required forms and agreements, and this provision ensures that authorized officers can execute these documents without requiring additional board action for each form. However, consider whether certain extraordinary documents or agreements should require specific board approval despite this general authorization.\n\n## Ratification, Effectiveness, and Ongoing Compliance\n\nInclude ratification language that validates any banking actions already taken on behalf of the corporation if individuals have opened accounts or conducted transactions before formal authorization. This ratification protects both the corporation and individuals who acted in good faith, preventing arguments that prior transactions lacked proper authority. Specify the effective date of the resolution, which may be the date of adoption or a future date if the banking relationship has not yet been established.\n\nAddress the relationship between this resolution and any prior banking resolutions by explicitly stating that this resolution supersedes and replaces any prior conflicting resolutions regarding banking authority. This prevents confusion about which authorization controls if multiple resolutions exist. Specify that the resolution remains in full force and effect until formally amended or revoked by subsequent board action, and require the corporation to provide certified copies of any amendments or revocations to the financial institution promptly.\n\nConsider including provisions that address what happens when authorized individuals leave their positions or when new officers are appointed. Some resolutions include automatic termination of authority upon an individual's separation from the corporation, while others require affirmative board action to revoke authority. Address whether the corporation must notify the bank when authorized signatories change and establish procedures for updating signature cards and banking records.\n\n## Certification, Execution, and Corporate Records\n\nConclude with a comprehensive certification section where the corporate secretary certifies the resolution's adoption and continuing validity. The certification should confirm that the resolution was duly adopted in accordance with the corporation's bylaws and applicable law, that it has not been amended or revoked, and that it remains in full force and effect as of the certification date. This certification provides the bank with assurance that the resolution represents current corporate authority.\n\nProvide appropriate signature blocks for the corporate secretary who certifies the resolution and any other officers whose signatures the bank may require. Each signature block should include lines for the signatory's printed name, corporate title, and date of signature. If the corporation maintains a corporate seal, include space for seal impression, as some financial institutions still require this formality despite its declining use in modern corporate practice.\n\n## Document Formatting and Professional Standards\n\nFormat the resolution in a manner consistent with formal corporate governance documents and suitable for presentation to financial institutions. Use clear section headings, numbered or lettered clauses for easy reference, and formal legal language that conveys the document's official nature while remaining comprehensible to bank personnel who will review it. The document should be suitable for printing on corporate letterhead and filing in the corporate minute book as part of the permanent corporate records.\n\nEnsure the final document includes all information that banks typically require in their due diligence review, including complete corporate identification, clear designation of authorized individuals, specific scope of authority, and proper certification. The resolution should be sufficiently detailed to satisfy banking compliance requirements while remaining flexible enough to accommodate normal business operations without requiring frequent amendments.\n\nIf you have access to the corporation's governing documents, prior resolutions, or information about specific banking needs, incorporate this information to create a tailored resolution that addresses the corporation's particular circumstances rather than a generic template. Search uploaded documents for relevant corporate information, officer and director names, existing banking relationships, and any special authorization requirements that should be reflected in the resolution.",
